\fs24 \cf2 \nosupersub \ulnone \strokec2 Saraha is known for being a wandering {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yogi"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 yogi}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avadhuta"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 avadhuta}} engaging in behaviors that overturned the social norms of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caste"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 caste}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_class"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 social class}}, and the oppressive normative {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gender_role"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 gender roles}} and hierarchies of the time. Two of Saraha's important teachers and consorts were women who were technically lower than him from the standpoint of caste, class, and gender. Yet, each of these nameless women met Saraha as an equal on the path of spiritual practice and each of them had the realization that led Saraha further in his own spiritual development. \
\
Saraha is normally shown seated and holding an arrow (Skt. \uc0\u347 aru). It is from a mature nameless woman, often called the Arrow Smith Dakini or the Arrow Making Dakini, who was Saraha's teacher and consort, that the typical iconography of Saraha holding an arrow emerges. Some versions of their meeting say that Saraha saw the Arrow Making Dakini in a vision and thus was wandering here and there, searching her out. Some say they met at a crossroads,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saraha#cite_note-5"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf4 \super \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 [5]}} while other versions say that it was in a busy marketplace where she was selling her arrows\
\
